Certainly! You can find the official Microsoft documentation on the Azure Databricks Managed Resource Group at the following link:

Azure Databricks managed resource group
https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/databricks/administration-guide/account-settings/managed-resource-group

Overview:
When you create an Azure Databricks workspace, Azure automatically creates a managed resource group in your subscription. This resource group contains resources required for the operation of your Databricks workspace, such as network interfaces and storage accounts.

Key Points:

Automatic Creation: The managed resource group is created by Azure Databricks during workspace deployment. You don't need to create it manually.
Naming Convention: The name usually follows the pattern databricks-rg-<workspace-name>-<random-string>.
Permissions: Ensure that the user or service principal deploying the workspace has the necessary permissions to create resources in your subscription, including the managed resource group.
Management: Do not modify or delete resources within this group directly. These resources are managed by Azure Databricks and changes might affect the stability of your workspace.
For more detailed information, including best practices and security considerations, please refer to the official documentation linked above.

If you have any more questions or need further assistance, feel free to ask!


```
# Upload single file using OAuth authentication
az storage blob upload \
  --account-name <STORAGE_ACCOUNT_NAME> \
  --container-name <CONTAINER_NAME> \
  --name <DESTINATION_BLOB_NAME> \
  --file <LOCAL_FILE_PATH> \
  --auth-mode login \
  --overwrite
```

```
az login --service-principal \
  --username <APP_ID> \
  --password <CLIENT_SECRET> \
  --tenant <TENANT_ID>

# Verify login
az account show
```

```
# List all private endpoints for a storage account
az network private-endpoint list \
  --resource-group <RESOURCE_GROUP> \
  --query "[? privateLinkServiceConnections[0].privateLinkServiceId==\
'/subscriptions/<SUBSCRIPTION_ID>/resourceGroups/<RESOURCE_GROUP>/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/<STORAGE_ACCOUNT_NAME>']" \
  --output table

# Alternative: Check by storage account directly
az network private-endpoint-connection list \
  --name <STORAGE_ACCOUNT_NAME> \
  --resource-group <RESOURCE_GROUP> \
  --type Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts \
  --output table

# Show all private endpoints in resource group
az network private-endpoint list \
  --resource-group <RESOURCE_GROUP> \
  --output table

# Get detailed info for specific private endpoint
az network private-endpoint show \
  --name <PRIVATE_ENDPOINT_NAME> \
  --resource-group <RESOURCE_GROUP> \
  --output json

# Check connection state for storage account
az storage account private-endpoint-connection list \
  --account-name <STORAGE_ACCOUNT_NAME> \
  --resource-group <RESOURCE_GROUP> \
  --output table

# Show detailed connection info
az storage account private-endpoint-connection show \
  --account-name <STORAGE_ACCOUNT_NAME> \
  --name <CONNECTION_NAME> \
  --resource-group <RESOURCE_GROUP>


```

```
foreach ($file in Get-ChildItem cert-*.crt) {
    $cert = New-Object System.Security.Cryptography.X509Certificates.X509Certificate2($file.FullName)
    Write-Host "`n$file"
    Write-Host " Subject: $($cert.Subject)"
    Write-Host " Issuer : $($cert.Issuer)"
    Write-Host " CA     : $($cert.Extensions | Where-Object { $_.Oid.FriendlyName -eq 'Basic Constraints' })"
}

```
